## Node Example

```{node}
const answer = 6 * 7;
console.log('node-like cwd:', process.cwd());
module.exports = { answer };
```
```+test
wrap(typeof process.cwd).should('equal', 'function').run('Node process API not available', 'Node process API available');
wrap(answer).should('equal', 42).run('Node computation failed', 'Node computation succeeded');
```

## Module Syntax Example

```{node}
import path from 'path';

export const lessonFile = path.basename('/workspace/lesson.txt');
console.log('lesson file:', lessonFile);
```
```+test
wrap(lessonFile).should('equal', 'lesson.txt').run('Module import/export did not run correctly', 'Module import/export worked');
```

```{css}
h1 {
  color: red;
}
```
```+html
<h1>Goodbye</h1>
```
```+test
assert('h1').should('exist').should('have.css', 'color: red').run('Failed to find red h1 rule', 'Found red h1 rule');
```

## React Example

```{react}
const App = () => {
  return (
    <section>
      <h2>React Cell</h2>
      <p id="react-message">Hello from JSX</p>
    </section>
  );
};

renderReact(<App />);
```
```+test
assert('#react-message').should('have.text', 'Hello from JSX').run('React output was not rendered', 'React output rendered correctly');
```

## JSX Alias + Custom Mount Example

```{jsx}
const ProductCard = ({ title, price }) => (
  <article className="card">
    <h3>{title}</h3>
    <p className="price">${price}</p>
  </article>
);

renderReact(<ProductCard title="Notebook Pro" price={49} />, '#app');
```
```+html
<div id="app"></div>
```
```+css
.card {
  border: 1px solid #ccc;
  border-radius: 8px;
  padding: 12px;
  max-width: 240px;
}

.price {
  font-weight: 700;
}
```
```+test
assert('#app h3').should('have.text', 'Notebook Pro').run('Failed to render JSX title', 'Rendered JSX title');
assert('#app .price').should('have.text', '$49').run('Failed to render JSX price', 'Rendered JSX price');
```

## Autorun Example

Here is a cell that runs automatically when you open the notebook:

```{javascript autorun}
console.log("Welcome to the notebook! This cell ran automatically.");
```

```{html autorun}
<h1>Welcome to the notebook!</h1>
<p>This cell ran automatically.</p>
```

## External Check Example

Create a directory named `external-example`. Inside it, create `index.html` and `styles.css`. The checklist below runs automatically and keeps checking every two seconds until all items pass.

```{external}
title: External project checklist
interval: 2s
- directory: external-example | Create a directory named `external-example`
- file: external-example/index.html | Inside `external-example`, create `index.html`
- contains: external-example/index.html | <h1 | In `index.html`, add an `h1` heading
- matches: external-example/index.html | /<title>.+<\/title>/ | In `index.html`, add a non-empty `title` element
```
```+files
external-example/styles.css
```
```+test
const stylesheetPath = 'external-example/styles.css';
checklist([
  check.file(stylesheetPath, 'Inside `external-example`, create `styles.css`'),
  check.file(stylesheetPath).contains('font-family', 'In `styles.css`, set a `font-family`')
]);
```

## Terminal Exercise Example

Practice a short terminal workflow in the simulated terminal below. Run these commands in order:

1. `mkdir terminal-example`
2. `cd terminal-example`
3. `npm init -y`

The checklist verifies each command appears in command history.

```{external}
title: Terminal setup practice
interval: 2s
- command: mkdir terminal-example | Create the exercise folder from the terminal
- command: cd terminal-example | Move into the exercise folder
- command: npm init -y | Initialize a package.json file
```
```+terminal
welcome: Run the setup commands shown above. This terminal is simulated.
prompt: $ 
```
```+test
checklist([
  check.commands(
    ['mkdir terminal-example', 'cd terminal-example', 'npm init -y'],
    'Run the setup commands in order'
  )
]);
```

## Terminal Test Helper Example

This example shows how to assert specific commands with both declarative and programmatic checks.

```{external}
title: Verify git setup commands
interval: 2s
- command: git init | Initialize a git repository
- command: git status | Run status to inspect the repository
```
```+terminal
welcome: Simulate a tiny git workflow.
prompt: $ 
```
```+test
checklist([
  check.command('git init', 'Run `git init`'),
  check.command('git status', 'Run `git status`'),
  check.commands(['git init', 'git status'], 'Run init before status'),
  {
    label: 'Use the terminal helper to verify `git status` ran',
    passed: terminal.didRun('git status'),
    detail: 'Expected terminal history to include `git status`.',
    run() {}
  }
]);
```

## Multiple Choice Examples

Single Correct Option with custom feedback:
```{mcq}
What is the capital of France?
correct: Nice work. Paris is the capital of France.
wrong: Not quite. Paris is the capital of France.
[ ] London
[x] Paris
[ ] Berlin
  wrong: Berlin is the capital of Germany, not France.
```

Multiple Correct Options:
```{mcq}
Which of the following are fruits? (Select all that apply)
correct: Correct. Apples and bananas are both fruits.
wrong: Try again. Check the per-item feedback for each choice.
[x] Apple
  correct: Apple is a fruit, so this should be selected.
  wrong: Apple is a fruit, so you should select it.
[ ] Carrot
  correct: Right. Carrot is a vegetable, so leave it unchecked.
  wrong: Carrot is a vegetable, so this should stay unchecked.
[x] Banana
  correct: Banana is a fruit, so this should be selected.
  wrong: Banana is a fruit, so you should select it.
[ ] Celery
  correct: Right. Celery is a vegetable, so leave it unchecked.
  wrong: Celery is a vegetable, so this should stay unchecked.
```

Question with default feedback:
```{mcq}
Which language runs in the browser in this notebook example?
[x] JavaScript
[ ] Rust
[ ] Go
```

Markdown Example:
```{mcq}
Which of the following creates a **bold** `text` element in HTML?
correct: Correct! The `<strong>` tag renders text strongly, typically in **bold**.
wrong: Nope! Try looking for a tag that implies *strong* importance.
[ ] `<em>text</em>`
  correct: `<em>` implies emphasis (often *italic*), not bold.
[x] `<strong>text</strong>`
  correct: Correct!
[ ] `<br>`
  correct: `<br>` is just a line break!
```
